\par }\pard\plain \s25\qj\li360\ri360\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 While the choir sings the psalm and the verses. The priest censes the altar and entire temple, without wearing his phelonion.
\par }\pard\plain \s32\qc\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx959\tx1918\tx2877\tx3836\tx4795\tx5754\tx6713\tx7672\tx8631\tx9590\adjustright \f2\fs20 {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 
\par \ldblquote Lord, I have cried\rdblquote  is sung in the tone of the first appointed sticheron.
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b\i {\*\bkmkstart h9}{\*\bkmkend h9}
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 In the ___ Tone: Lord, I have cried unto Thee, hearken unto me.
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Lord, I have cried unto Thee, hearken unto me. * Hearken unto me, O Lord. * Lord, I have cried unto Thee, hearken unto me; * attend to the voice of my supplication, * wh
en I cry unto Thee. * Hearken unto me, O Lord.
\par Let my prayer be set forth * as incense before Thee, * the lifting up of my hands * as an evening sacrifice. * Hearken unto me, O Lord.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And the rest of the verses are read (they can be sung at a vigil) down to the beginning of the stichoi, i.e. the point at which the stichera are inserted.
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{\b\i  }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Set, O Lord, a watch before my mouth, and a door of enclosure round about my lips.
\par Incline not my heart unto words of evil, to make excuse with excuses in sins.
\par With men that work iniquity; and I will not join with their chosen.
\par The righteous man will chasten me with mercy and reprove me; as for the oil of the sinner, let it not anoint my head.
\par For yet more is my prayer in the presence of their pleasures; swallowed up near by the rock have their judges been.
\par They shall hear my words, for they be sweetened; as a clod of earth is broken upon the earth, so have their bones been scattered nigh unto hades.
\par For unto Thee, O Lord, O Lord, are mine eyes, in Thee have I hoped; take not my soul away.
\par Keep me from the snare which they have laid for me, and from the stumbling-blocks of them that work iniquity.
\par The sinners shall fall into their own net; I am alone until I pass by.
\par With my voice unto the Lord have I cried, with my voice unto the Lord have I made supplication.
\par I will pour out before Him my supplication, mine affliction before Him will I declare.
\par When my spirit was fainting within me, then Thou knewest my paths.
\par In this way wherein I have walked they hid for me a snare. 
\par I looked upon my right hand, and beheld, and there was none that did know me.
\par Flight hath failed me, and there is none that watcheth out for my soul.
\par I have cried unto Thee, O Lord; I said: Thou art my hope, my portion art Thou in the land of the living.
\par Attend unto my supplication, for I am brought very low.
\par Deliver me from them that persecute me, for they are stronger than I.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 If there are 10 stichera (Saturday evenings and Liturgies of the Presanctified):
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (10)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Bring my soul out of prison}{: 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 that I may confess Thy name.}{ 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And then is sung the first stichera, and likewise are sung the rest of the stichoi.
\par (9)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 The righteous shall wait patiently for me }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * until Thou shalt reward me.
\par }{\cs60\i\f1\fs36\cf15 If there are 8 stichera (services of vigil or polyeleos rank):
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6  (8)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Out of the depths have I cried unto Thee, O Lord;}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * O Lord, hear my voice.
\par }{ }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (7)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Let Thine ears be attentive}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * to the voice of my supplication.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 If there are 6 stichera (all services of doxology rank, and all simple services, i.e., 6 stichera from the Menaion, or 3 from the Octoechos and 3 from the Menaion):
\par (6)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 If Thou shouldest mark iniquities, O Lord, O Lord, who shall stand?}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * For with Thee there is forgiveness.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (5)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 For Thy name\rquote s sake have I patiently waited for Thee, O Lord; my soul hath patiently waited for Thy word, }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * my soul hath hoped in the Lord.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 If there are 4 stichera (only at Small Vespers):
\par  (4)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 From the morning watch until night, from the morning watch}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * let Israel hope in the Lord.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (3)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 For with the Lord there is mercy, and with Him is plenteous redemption;}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * and He shall redeem Israel out of all his iniquities.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (2)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 O praise the Lord, all ye nations;}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * praise Him, all ye peoples.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (1)}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 For He hath made His mercy to prevail over us,}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 * and the truth of the Lord abideth forever.
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Glory in the _ tone
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6  Sticheron (Doxasticon) from the Menaion, if there is one. If there is a feast of the Lord or of the Theotokos: \ldblquote Glory\'85 Both now\'85\rdblquote  and the Theotokion of the feast.
\par }{ }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Both now and ever, and unto the ages of ages. Amen.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And we then sing the Dogmatic Theotokion of the tone, or as appointed in the Menaion. 
\par During the singing of the Theotokion, the priest and deacon make the Small entrance with the censer. The priest silently says the prayer of the entry: 
\par }\pard \qc\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 
\par Prayer of the Entry}{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 
\par }\pard\plain \s45\qj\li576\ri576\sb100\sa100\sl360\slmult1\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs36\cf15 {\b\i Priest:}{ 
\par Evening, morning and noonday \'85
\par }\pard\plain \s25\qj\li360\ri360\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 When the prayer is ended, the deacon says to the priest, pointing toward the east with his right hand, holding therein his orarion with three fingers:
\par }\pard\plain \s45\qj\li576\ri576\sb100\sa100\sl360\slmult1\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs36\cf15 {\b\i\fs28\cf16 Deacon (only):}{ Bless, master, the holy entrance.
\par }\pard\plain \s25\li360\ri360\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 And the priest, blessing, saith:
\par }\pard\plain \s45\qj\li576\ri576\sb100\sa100\sl360\slmult1\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f1\fs36\cf15 {\b\i Priest:}{ Blessed is the entry of Thy holy ones always, now and ever and unto the ages of ages.
\par }{\b\i Deacon:}{ Amen.}{\fs32 
\par }\pard\plain \s25\qj\li360\ri360\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 When the final verse of the Theotokion hath been finished, the deacon goes
 to the center, and standing in front of the priest, raiseth the censer, and making the sign of the cross with it, says in a loud voice:}{\fs32  
\par }\pard\plain \qj\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\intbl\adjustright {\cs43\b\i\f1\fs28 Deacon:}{\fs32  }{\cs47\b\fs36 Wisdom! Aright!}{\cs43\b\i\f1\fs28 \cell }\pard \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\intbl\adjustright {\cs43\b\i\f1133\fs28 \'c4\'e8\'e0\'ea\'ee\'ed:}{
\cs43\b\i\f1\fs28  }{\cs47\b\f1127\fs36 \'cf\'f0\'e5\'ec\'f3\'e4\'f0\'ee\'f1\'f2\'fc, \'ef\'f0\'ee\'f1\'f2\'e8!}{\cs43\b\i\f1\fs28 \cell }\pard \widctlpar\intbl\adjustright {\cs43\b\i\f1\fs28 \row }\pard\plain 
\s25\qj\li360\ri360\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\fs28\cf6 Then, having bowed, as also the priest behind him, he goeth into the holy altar; 
\par And the singers chant:
\par }\pard\plain \qj\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 
O Gladsome Light of the holy glory of the immortal, heavenly, holy, blessed Father, O Jesus Christ: Having come to the setting of the sun, having beheld the evening light, we praise the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit: God. 
Meet it is for Thee at all times to be praised with reverent voices, O Son of God, Giver of life. Wherefore, the world doth glorify Thee.
\par }\pard \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\cf6 The clergy stand in the High place, facing West. At the end of the hymn, the prokeimenon is chanted: 
