\par }\pard \qj\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Then we sing the Polyeleos (Psa
lm 134 and 135), but usually only the following four verses (the first and last verses of each psalm), on all Sundays from September 21 until December 20 and from January 14 through Cheese-Fare Sunday. 
\par Beginning on the First Sunday of Great Lent until the Sunday after September 21, there is no Polyeleos on Sundays, except for Palm Sunday and Pentecost, unless appointed by the Menaion, and we sing (or read) \ldblquote The Blameless,\rdblquote 
 i.e. Psalm 118, followed by the Evlogitaria. 
\par }\pard \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {
\par THE POLYELEOS
\par (Select verses):
\par 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Praise ye the name of the Lord; O ye servants, praise the Lord. Alleluia, alleluia, alleluia. 
\par Blessed is the Lord out of Zion, who dwelleth in Jerusalem. Alleluia, alleluia, alleluia.
\par O give thanks unto the Lord, for He is good; for His mercy endureth forever. Alleluia, alleluia, alleluia.
\par O give thanks unto the God of heaven; for His mercy endureth forever. Alleluia, alleluia, alleluia.
\par }{
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 [On the Sunday of the Prodigal Son, Meat-Fare, and Cheese-Fare Sundays, after the Polyeleos we sing Psalm 136: \ldblquote By the rivers of Babylon\'85\rdblquote ]
\par }{ 
\par  Then, in Slavic practice, the Megalynarion of the feast is sung, if there is one, with the selected psalm verses. However, if it is a Sunday, the Megalynarion is usually sung only once (in general parish pract
ice), without psalm verses, unless it is a Great feast of the Lord.
\par  
\par THE EVLOGITARIA (On Sundays)
\par  
\par }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Blessed art Thou, O Lord, * teach me Thy statutes.
\par The assembly of angels was amazed, * beholding Thee numbered among the dead; * yet, O Savior, * destroying the stronghold of death, * and with Thyself raising up Adam, * and freeing all from hades.
\par Blessed art Thou, O Lord, * teach me Thy statutes.
\par Why mingle ye myrrh with tears of pity, * O ye women disciples? * Thus the radiant angel within the tomb * addressed the myrrh-bearing women; * behold the tomb and understand, * for the Savior is risen from the tomb.
\par Blessed art Thou, O Lord, * teach me Thy statutes.
\par Very early * the myrrh-bearing women hastened * unto Thy tomb, lamenting, * but the angel stood before them and said: * the time for lamentation is passed, weep not, * but tell of the Resurrection to the apostles.
\par Blessed art Thou, O Lord, * teach me Thy statutes.
\par The myrrh-bearing women, * with myrrh came to Thy tomb, O Savior, bewailing, * but the angel addressed them, saying: * Why number ye the living among the dead, * for as God * He is risen from the tomb.
\par Glory to the Father, and to the Son, * and to the Holy Spirit.
\par Let us worship the Father, * and His Son, and the Holy Spirit, * the Holy Trinity, * one in essence, * crying with the Seraphim: * Holy, Holy, Holy art Thou, O Lord.
\par Both now and ever, * and unto the ages of ages. Amen.
\par In bringing forth the Giver of life, * thou hast delivered Adam from sin, O Virgin, * and hast brought joy to Eve * instead of sorrow; * and those fallen from life * have thereunto been restored, * by Him Who of thee was incarnate, God and man.
\par Alleluia, alleluia, alleluia. Glory to Thee, O God.}{ }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Thrice.}{
\par  
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Lord, have mercy}{. Thrice 
\par 
\par  }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto the ages of ages. 
\par }{
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Amen.
\par }\pard \qj\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs44\i\f1\cf6 If it is Sunday, the Hypakoe is read (if feast of the Theotokos or of saints fall on Sunday, their sessional hymns are read after the Hypakoe. Fea
st of the Lord which fall on Sunday replace the Octoechos entirely).
\par Then, on Sundays the Hymns of Ascents of the tone are sung. On feasts of the Lord and at vigils on other days only the first antiphon of the 4th tone is sung, as follows:
\par }\pard \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright { }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 From my youth * do many passions war against me; * but do Thou Thyself defend * and save me, O my Savior.
\par Ye haters of Zion * shall be shamed by the Lord; * for like grass, by the fire * shall ye be withered.
\par Glory to the Father, and to the Son, * and to the Holy Spirit, * both now and ever, * and unto the ages of ages. Amen.
\par In the Holy Spirit, * every soul is quickened, * and, through cleansing, is exalted * and made radiant by the Triple Unity in a hidden sacred manner.
\par }{ Deacon: The Prokimenon in the ___ Tone:
\par  }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And he reads the Prokimenon of the Sunday tone, or of the feast. The choir sings it; he then reads the stichos; the choir repeats the Prokimenon; he then reads the 
first half of the Prokimenon (down to the asterisk), and the choir sings the remaining portion.
\par }{
\par }{\cs47\b\fs36 The Prokimena for Sunday Matins:}{
\par 
\par }{\cs47\b\fs36 Tone 1: Now will I arise, saith the Lord; I will establish them in salvation, * I will be manifest therein.
\par }\pard \fi720\li720\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs47\b\fs36 Stichos: The words of the Lord are pure words.
\par }\pard \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs47\b\fs36  
\par Tone 2: Arouse Thyself, O Lord my God, in the commandment which Thou hast enjoined, * and a congregation of peoples shall surround Thee.
\par  Stichos: O Lord my God, in Thee have I put my hope; save me.
\par  
\par Tone 3: Say among the nations that the Lord is king; * for He hath established the world which shall not be shaken.
\par  Stichos: O sing unto the Lord a new song, sing unto the Lord all the earth.
\par  
\par Tone 4: Arise, O Lord, help us, * and redeem us for Thy name\rquote s sake.
\par  Stichos: O God, with our ears have we heard, for our fathers have told us.
\par  
\par Tone 5: Arise, O Lord my God, let Thy hands be lifted high; * for Thou shalt be king forever.
\par  Stichos: I will confess Thee, O Lord, with my whole heart, I will tell of all Thy wonders.
\par  
\par Tone 6: O Lord, stir up Thy might * and come to save us.
\par  Stichos: O Shepherd of Israel, attend, Thou that leadest Joseph like a sheep.
\par  
\par Tone 7: Arise, O Lord my God, let Thy hand be lifted high; * forget not Thy paupers to the end.
\par  Stichos: I will confess Thee, O Lord, with my whole heart, I will tell of all Thy wonders.
\par  
\par Tone 8: The Lord shall be king unto eternity; * thy God, O Zion, unto generation and generation.
\par  Stichos: Praise the Lord, O my soul. I will praise the Lord in my life.
\par }{ 
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Let every breath praise the Lord.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ Let every breath praise the Lord.
\par  
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Praise ye God in His saints, praise Him in the firmament of His power.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ Let every breath praise the Lord.
\par  
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Let every breath. 
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Praise the Lord.
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Lord, have mercy}{. }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Thrice.}{
\par  
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ The reading is from the Holy Gospel according to Saint _____.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Glory to Thee, O Lord, glory to Thee.
\par }{ 
\par  Then the Senior reader reads the appointed Gospel, in a normal tone of voice, facing the altar. At the conclusion of the reading:
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Glory to Thee, O Lord, glory to Thee.}{
\par  
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And on Sundays (except Palm Sunday and Pentecost), and on Ascension, and on the Exaltation of the Cross, and on any weekday or Saturday vigil of the Paschal period, 
once (but on Thomas Sunday and the rest of the Sundays of the Paschal period through the Sunday of the Blind Man, thrice):
\par }{ }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Having beheld the Resurrection of Christ, * let us worshi
p the holy Lord Jesus, * the only sinless One. * We venerate Thy Cross, O Christ, * and Thy holy Resurrection we hymn and glorify. * For Thou art our God, * and we know none other beside Thee; * we call upon Thy name. * O come, all ye faithful, * let us w
orship Christ\rquote s holy Resurrection, * for, behold, through the Cross joy hath come to all the world. * Ever blessing the Lord, * we hymn His Resurrection; * for, having endured crucifixion, * He hath destroyed death by death.
\par }{ 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s55\qc\widctlpar\adjustright \b\i\f1\fs32\cf6\lang1024\cgrid {\cs51\b0\f0\fs36 PSALM 50 
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard\plain \s55\qj\widctlpar\adjustright \b\i\f1\fs32\cf6\lang1024\cgrid {\cs54\i0\fs24 Reader:}{\b0\i0\cf0\lang1033\cgrid0  }{\b0\i0\cf0\lang1033\cgrid0 
Have mercy on me, O God, according to Thy great mercy; and according to the multitude of Thy compassions blot out my transgression. 
\par 
\par Wash me thoroughly from mine iniquity, and cleanse me from my sin. 
\par 
\par For I know mine iniquity, and my sin is ever before me. 
\par 
\par Against Thee only have I sinned and done this evil before Thee, that Thou mightest be justified in Thy words, and prevail when Thou art judged. 
\par 
\par For behold, I was conceived in iniquities, and in sins did my mother bear me. 
\par 
\par For behold, Thou hast loved truth; the hidden and secret things of Thy wisdom hast Thou made manifest unto me. 
\par 
\par Thou shalt sprinkle me with hyssop, and I shall be made clean; Thou shalt wash me, and I shall be made whiter than snow. 
\par 
\par Thou shalt make me to hear joy and gladness; the bones that be humbled, they shall rejoice. 
\par 
\par Turn Thy face away from my sins, and blot out all mine iniquities. 
\par 
\par Create in me a clean heart, O God, and renew a right spirit within me. 
\par 
\par Cast me not away from Thy presence, and take not Thy Holy Spirit from me. 
\par 
\par Restore unto me the joy of Thy salvation, and with Thy governing Spirit establish me. 
\par 
\par I shall teach transgressors Thy ways, and the ungodly shall turn back unto Thee. 
\par 
\par Deliver me from blood-guiltiness, O God, Thou God of my salvation; my tongue shall rejoice in Thy righteousness. 
\par 
\par O Lord, Thou shalt open my lips, and my mouth shall declare Thy praise. 
\par 
\par For if Thou hadst desired sacrifice, I had given it; with whole-burnt offerings Thou shalt not be pleased. 
\par 
\par A sacrifice unto God is a broken spirit; a heart that is broken and humbled God will not despise. 
\par 
\par Do good, O Lord, in Thy good pleasure unto Sion, and let the walls of Jerusalem be builded. 
\par 
\par Then shalt Thou be pleased with a sacrifice of righteousness, with oblation and whole-burnt offerings. 
\par 
\par Then shall they offer bullocks upon Thine altar.
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright { 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 If it is a feast of the Lord or The Entry of the Theotokos into the Temple, with special stichera, they are sung here. Otherwise, on Sundays and other vigils we sing in the
\par 6th Tone:
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and the Holy Spirit.
\par Through the prayers of the apostles }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 (or the Theotokos, on her feasts, or Saint N., if it is not a Sunday vigil),}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  O Merciful One, * blot out the multitude of our transgressions.
\par Both now and ever, and unto the ages of ages. Amen.
\par Through the prayers of the Theotokos, * O Merciful One, * blot out the multitude of our transgressions.
\par Have mercy on me, O God, * according to Thy great mercy; * and according to the multitude of Thy compassions, * blot out my transgressions.
\par  
\par }{ And if there is a festal sticheron appointed at this place (for feasts of the Lord and the Theotokos, on any day, including Sundays; for saints, on weekdays only), it is
\par sung. Otherwise, on Sundays outside the Lenten cycle we sing:
\par  
\par  }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Jesus having risen from the grave, * as He foretold, * hath given us life eternal, * and great mercy.
\par  
\par 
\par  
\par }{
\par  
\par  }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 But beginning with the Sunday of the Publican and the Pharisee and continuing through the 5th Sunday of Lent, immediately after the 50th Psalm we sing, instead of the preceding verses, the following:
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Tone 8}{: }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit.
\par The doors of repentance do Thou open to me, O Giver of life, * for my spirit waketh at dawn toward Thy holy temple, * bearing a temple of the body all defiled. * But in Thy compassion cleanse it * by the loving-kindness of Thy mercy.
\par 
\par Both now and ever, and unto the ages of ages. Amen.
\par 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Theotokion: }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Guide me in the paths of salvation, O Theotokos, * for I have defiled my soul with shameful sins, * and have wasted all my life in
\par slothfulness, * but by thine intercessions * deliver me from all uncleanness.
\par }{Tone 6: }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Have mercy on me, O God, * according to Thy great mercy; * and according to the multitude of Thy compassions, * blot out my transgressions.
\par When I think of the multitude of evil things I have done, * I, a wretched one, * I tremble at the fearful day of judgment; * but trusting in the mercy of
\par  Thy loving-kindness, * like David do I cry unto Thee: * Have mercy on me, O God, * according to Thy great mercy.
\par }{
\par  
\par 
\par 
\par  
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Lord, have mercy. Twelve Times.
\par  
\par  O Lord, Jesus Christ, Son of God, have mercy on us.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Amen.
\par }{ 
\par  Then we begin the canon. After the 3rdand 6th odes:
\par  
\par 
\par Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Lord, have mercy. Thrice 
\par 
\par  Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto the ages of ages. 
\par 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Amen.
\par }{
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 After the 8th Ode of the canon, we sing:
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 We praise, we bless, we worship the Lord, praising and supremely exalting Him unto all ages.}{ And then the appointed katavasia.
\par  
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And we sing the Song of the Most Holy Theotokos (the Magnificat) (on great feasts special megalynaria are sung instead of the Magnificat):
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 My soul doth magnify the Lord, * and my spirit hath rejoiced in God my Savior.
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 And after each verse, the refrain:}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  
\par }\pard \qj\sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 More honorable than the Cherubim, * and beyond compare more glorious than the Seraphim; * who without
\par corruption gavest birth to God the Word, * the very Theotokos, thee do we magnify.
\par }\pard \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 For He hath looked upon the lowliness of His handmaiden; * for behold, from henceforth all generations shall call me blessed. }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Refrain.}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 
\par For the Mighty One hath done great things to me, * and holy is His name; * and His mercy is on them that fear Him * unto generation and generation. }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Refrain.}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 
\par He hath showed strength with His arm, * and He hath scattered the proud in the imagination of their heart. }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Refrain.}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 
\par He hath put down the mighty from their seat, * and exalted them of low degree; * He hath filled the hungry with good things, * and the rich He hath sent empty away. }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Refrain.}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 
\par He hath holpen His servant Israel * in remembrance of His mercy, * as He spake to our fathers, * to Abraham and his seed forever. }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Refrain.
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 After the 9th ode:
\par }{Senior }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Lord, have mercy. Thrice 
\par 
\par Glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, both now and ever, and unto the ages of ages. 
\par 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Amen.
\par }{
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Then, if it is Sunday (but not on Pascha, Pentecost, or any Sunday coinciding with Transfiguration or the Exaltation of the Cross):
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Holy is the Lord our God.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Holy is the Lord our God.
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ For holy is the Lord our God.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Holy is the Lord our God.
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ Above all peoples is our God.
\par  
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Holy is the Lord our God.
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 After this, the Exapostilaria of the Resurrection and / or the feast.
\par  
\par }\pard\plain \s55\qc\widctlpar\adjustright \b\i\f1\fs32\cf6\lang1024\cgrid {\cs44\i0 The Lauds (the Praises) in the tone of the first appointed sticheron:
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright { 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 Let every breath praise the Lord. * Praise the Lord from the heavens, * praise Him in the highest. * To Thee is due praise, O God.
\par Praise Him, all ye His angels; * praise Him, all ye His hosts. * To Thee is due praise, O God.
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 Then, straight chant on one note, as on \ldblquote do,\rdblquote  going up one step on the next-to-the-last word(s) or syllable(s) and back down again on the last stressed word(s) or syllable(s). 
The word(s) or syllable(s) which should be raised one note are in boldface type. Also, the verses may be read down to the last verse before the first sticheron is sung.
\par }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Praise Him, O sun and moon; praise Him all ye stars and light.
\par Praise Him, ye heavens of heavens, and thou water that art above the heav-ens.
\par Let them praise the name of the Lord; for He spake, and they came to be; He commanded, and they were cre-at-ed.
\par He established them for ever, yea, for ever and ever; He hath set an ordinance, and it shall not pass a-way.
\par Praise the Lord from the earth, ye dragons, and all ye a-byss-es.
\par Fire, hail, snow, ice, blast of tempest, which per-form His word.
\par The mountains and all the hills, fruitful trees, and all ce-dars.
\par The beasts and all the cattle, creeping things and wing-ed birds.
\par Kings of the earth, and all peoples, princes and all the judges of the earth.
\par Young men and virgins, elders with the younger; let them praise the name of the Lord, for exalted is the name of Him a-lone.
\par His praise is above the earth and heaven, and He shall exalt the horn of His peo-ple.
\par This is the hymn for all His saints, for the sons of Israel, and for the people that draw nigh unto Him.
\par Sing unto the Lord a new song; His praise is in the church of the saints.
\par Let Israel be glad in Him that made him, let the sons of Zion re-joice in their King.
\par Let them praise His name in the dance; with the timbrel and the psaltery let them chant unto Him.
\par For the Lord taketh pleasure in His people, and He shall exalt the meek with sal-va-tion.
\par The saints shall boast in glory, and they shall re-joice upon their beds.
\par The high praise of God shall be in their throat, and two-edged swords shall be in their hands.
\par To do vengeance among the heathen, punishments among the peo-ples.
\par To bind their kings with fetters, and their nobles with manacles of i-ron.
\par  
\par }{\cs44\i\f1\cf6 If there are 6 (or 8) stichera appointed, they are sung after the following verse, otherwise it is read or sung as the above verses down to the place were we would begin when 4 stichera are appointed:
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs54\i\f1 Reader:}{ }{\cs53\f1\fs32 To do among them the judgment that is written. 
\par }{ 
\par }{\cs59\b\i\f1\fs28\cf15 Choir:}{ }{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15 This glory shall be to all His saints}{. And then the first sticheron is sung.
\par }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Praise ye God in His saints,}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  * praise Him in the firmament of His power. }{Sticheron.
\par  
\par }\pard\plain \s55\qc\widctlpar\adjustright \b\i\f1\fs32\cf6\lang1024\cgrid { If there are 4 stichera appointed, they begin after the following verse:
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright { 
\par  }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Praise Him for His mighty acts,}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  * praise Him according to the multitude of His greatness.}{ Sticheron.
\par }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Praise Him with the sound of trumpet,}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  * praise Him with the psaltery and harp.}{ Sticheron.
\par }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Praise Him with timbrel and dance,}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  * praise him with strings and flute.}{ Sticheron.
\par }{\cs53\f1\fs32 Praise Him with tuneful cymbals, praise Him with cymbals of jubilation.}{\cs60\f1\fs36\cf15  * Let every breath praise the Lord}{. Sticheron.
